{"title_page": "Penny O'Donnell", "text_new": "\n\n'''Dr Penny O'Donnell''' is a bilingual radio journalist, author and media scholar, best known for her research into global journalism, comparative media, and the effects of digital transformation on job losses among Australian journalists. \n\n== Biography ==\nO'Donnell received a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) from [[University of Melbourne]] in 1981, a Masters of Social Communication from the [[Iberoamericana University]], Mexico, in 1993 and her PhD from [[University of Technology Sydney|University of Technology,]] Sydney in 2006. A former journalist for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC), she began lecturing at the School of Journalism at the [[Central American University (Managua)|Central American University]] in Managua, Nicaragua, before returning to Australia to teach at [[University of Technology Sydney]], receiving a Team Teaching Award for creating new dialogues about race, power, subjectivity, and intercultural communication<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/penny-odonnell-12067|title=Penny O'Donnell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. She joined [[University of Sydney]] as Senior Lecturer in International Media and Journalism in 2008, where she is also Degree Director for the Master of Media Practice.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydney.edu.au/arts/about/our-people/academic-staff/staff-profile.html|title=Staff Profile|website=The University of Sydney|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> O'Donnell serves on the Editorial Board of ''Journalism and Mass Communication Educator'' and the Advisory Board of ''Global Media Journal \u2014 Australian edition.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hca.westernsydney.edu.au/gmjau/?page_id=45|title=Global Media Journal: Australian Edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nO'Donnell's interest in Central American culture and media started when she was sent by the ABC to cover the 1986 International Peace March. She returned a year later to Nicaragua for three years and published two books about the experience. The first, ''Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua'', is a travel memoir which also provides a case study to demonstrate the importance of radio education for impoverished communities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arnove|first=Robert|title=Comparative Education: The Dialectic of the Global and the Local|publisher=Rowan & Littlefield|year=2013|isbn=978-1442217768|location=|pages=216}}</ref> Her second book, ''Dar la palabra al pueblo,'' was about teaching communication. Written in Spanish, it was published by the Iberoamericana Universidad, Mexico.  \n\nIn 1995, after returning to Australia, she co-authored the book ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia.'' In 2012 she co-authored a monograph, ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century,'' about job losses among Australian journalists brought by the disruption of digital media. \n\nO'Donnell has co-authored submissions to Australian government inquiries into the media and journalism, including [[Raymond Finkelstein|Hon R Finklestein']]<nowiki/>s 2012 inquiry into media regulation, the 2017 Future of Public Interest Journalism Inquiry, and in 2018 the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers. \n\nO'Donnell is a member of:\n\n* International Communication Association (ICA)\n*International Association for Media and Communication Research (IAMCR)\n* Journalism Education and Research Association of Australia (JERAA)<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<br />\n=== Australian Research Council ===\nO'Donnell was funded by the [[Australian Research Council]] (ARC) in 2009 as Lead Chief Investigator into the future of newspapers, along with Associate Professor David McKnight, from [[University of New South Wales]]. In 2012 she became Chief Investigator on the ARC-funded New Beats Project, which involved seven journalism academics from five Australian universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/the-new-beats-team/|title=The New Beats team|date=2013-11-27|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The study focused on the mass redundancies of 3000 journalists who lost their jobs in Australia between 2012 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.org.au/articles/exiting-journalists-marching-new-beat-survey-finds|title=Exiting journalists marching to a new beat, survey finds|website=The Citizen|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/new-research-reveals-how-australian-journalists-are-faring-four-years-after-redundancy-107520|title=New research reveals how Australian journalists are faring four years after redundancy|last=Dodd|first=Andrew|last2=Zion|first2=Lawrie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ricketson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherwood|first4=Merryn|last5=Winarnita|first5=Monika|last6=O'Donnell|first6=Penny|last7=Marjoribanks|first7=Timothy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au|title=Study follows new beats in journalism|last=Sinclair|first=Lara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>. A second round of ARC funding allowed the research to expand internationally and New Beats II included collaborators such as [[:nl:Mark_Deuze|Professor Mark Deuze]] in the Netherlands, as well as academics in America, Canada, Indonesia and South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/|title=New Beats|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== Books ===\nO'Donnell, Penny (1991) ''Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua,'' ABC Enterprises, Crows Nest, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, Penelope (1995) ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista'' (Giving the word to the people: the teaching-learning of communication in Nicaragua during the Sandinista Popular Revolution), Universidad Iberoamericana, Mexico.\n\nO'Donnell, Penny & Simons, Lynette (1995) ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia,'' Pluto Press, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, P., McKnight, D., Este, J. (2012). ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century''. Sydney, Australia: Walkley Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/meaa/docs/2012_journalism_speed_of_bytes|title=Journalism at the speed of bytes|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Submissions ===\n\n\n*O'Donnell, P., Zion, L., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2018), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers from the New Beats Project, Submission 140''.\n* Zion, L., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., O'Donnell, P., Ricketson, M., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2017), ''New Beats Project Submission to the Senate Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 37''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Future_of_Public_Interest_Journalism/PublicInterestJournalism/Submissions|title=Submissions|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Dwyer, T., Martin, F., O'Donnell, P. (2017), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 44. June 2017''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n<br />\n== Selected scholarly publications ==\n\n* O'Donnell, P., Zion, L. (2019). Precarity in Media Work. In Mark Deuze, Mirjam Prenger (Eds.), ''Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions'', (pp. 223\u2013234). Amsterdam: Amsterdam University Press<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|title=Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions|date=2019-01-14|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=|isbn=978-90-485-4015-0|editor-last=Deuze|editor-first=Mark|location=|pages=|doi=10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|editor-last2=Prenger|editor-first2=Mirjam}}</ref>\n* Cohen, N., Hunter, A., O'Donnell, P. (2019). Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism. ''Journalism Practice'', 13(7), (pp. 817\u2013833)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|last2=Hunter|first2=Andrea|last3=O\u2019Donnell|first3=Penny|date=2019-08-09|title=Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|journal=Journalism Practice|volume=13|issue=7|pages=817\u2013833|doi=10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|issn=1751-2786}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2018). Australian Journalists at Work. In Eric Freedman, Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions: Global Experiences'', (pp. 24\u201334). New York: Routledge<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/|title=Australian Journalists at Work : Their Views on Employment, Unionization, and Professional Identity|last=O\u2019Donnell|first=Penny|date=2018-05-11|website=Critical Perspectives on Journalistic Beliefs and Actions|language=en|doi=10.4324/9781315161099-3|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Zion, L., Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P., Marjoribanks, T., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Winarnita, M. (2018). ''New Beats Report: Mass redundancies and career change in Australian journalism'', (pp. 1\u201328). Melbourne, Australia: The New Beats Project\n* Sherwood, M., O'Donnell, P. (2018). Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist? Industry Restructure, Job Loss and Professional Identity. ''Journalism Studies'', 19(7), 1021\u20131038<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherwood|first=Merryn|last2=O\u2019Donnell|first2=Penny|date=2018-05-19|title=Once a Journalist, Always a Journalist?|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|journal=Journalism Studies|volume=19|issue=7|pages=1021\u20131038|doi=10.1080/1461670X.2016.1249007|issn=1461-670X}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2017). Journalism Education in Australia: Educating Journalists for Convergent, Cosmopolitan, and Uncertain News Environments.  In Robyn S. Goodman, Elanie Steyn (Eds.), ''Global Journalism Education in the 21st Century: Challenges and Innovations'', (pp. 17\u201340). Austin: The University of Texas at Austin\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\nPersonal Blog: https://pennyodonnell.com/\n\nNew Beats Project: http://www.newbeatsblog.com/\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:O'Donnell, Penny}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Technology Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Dr Penny O'Donnell''' is a bilingual radio journalist, author and media scholar, best known for her research into global journalism, comparative media, and the effects of digital transformation on job losses among Australian journalists. \n\n== Biography ==\nO'Donnell received a Bachelor of Arts (Honours) from [[University of Melbourne]] in 1981, a Masters of Social Communication from the [[Iberoamericana University]], Mexico, in 1993 and her PhD from [[University of Technology Sydney|University of Technology,]] Sydney in 2006. A former journalist for the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] (ABC), she began lecturing at the School of Journalism at the [[Central American University (Managua)|Central American University]] in Managua, Nicaragua, before returning to Australia to teach at [[University of Technology Sydney]], receiving a Team Teaching Award for creating new dialogues about race, power, subjectivity, and intercultural communication<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/profiles/penny-odonnell-12067|title=Penny O'Donnell|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>. She joined [[University of Sydney]] as Senior Lecturer in International Media and Journalism in 2008, where she is also Degree Director for the Master of Media Practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydney.edu.au/arts/about/our-people/academic-staff/staff-profile.html|title=Staff Profile|website=The University of Sydney|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> O'Donnell serves on the Editorial Board of ''Journalism and Mass Communication Educator'' and the Advisory Board of ''Global Media Journal \u2014 Australian edition.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hca.westernsydney.edu.au/gmjau/?page_id=45|title=Global Media Journal: Australian Edition|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nO'Donnell's interest in Central American culture and media started when she was sent by the ABC to cover the 1986 International Peace March. She returned a year later to Nicaragua for three years where she completed her Masters of Social Communication, taught journalism and became fluent in Spanish. She published a book about the experience, which provides a case study that demonstrates the importance of radio education for impoverished communities.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Arnove|first=Robert|title=Comparative Education: The Dialectic of the Global and the Local|publisher=Rowan & Littlefield|year=2013|isbn=978-1442217768|location=|pages=216}}</ref> Her second book, ''Dar la palabra al pueblo,'' was about teaching communication. Written in Spanish, it was published by the  Iberoamericana Universidad, Mexico. In 1995, after returning to Australia, she co-authored the book ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia.'' \n\nO'Donnell is a member of:\n\n* International Communication Association (ICA)\n*International Association for Media and Communication Research (IAMCR)\n* Journalism Education and Research Association of Australia (JERAA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sydney.edu.au/arts/about/our-people/academic-staff/staff-profile.html|title=Staff Profile|website=The University of Sydney|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n=== Australian Research Council ===\nO'Donnell was funded by the [[Australian Research Council]] (ARC) in 2009 as Lead Chief Investigator into the future of newspapers, along with Associate Professor David McKnight, from [[University of New South Wales]]. In 2012 she became Chief Investigator on the ARC-funded New Beats Project, which involved seven journalism academics from five Australian universities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/the-new-beats-team/|title=The New Beats team|date=2013-11-27|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The study focused on the mass redundancies of 3000 journalists who lost their jobs in Australia between 2012 and 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecitizen.org.au/articles/exiting-journalists-marching-new-beat-survey-finds|title=Exiting journalists marching to a new beat, survey finds|website=The Citizen|language=en-au|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/new-research-reveals-how-australian-journalists-are-faring-four-years-after-redundancy-107520|title=New research reveals how Australian journalists are faring four years after redundancy|last=Dodd|first=Andrew|last2=Zion|first2=Lawrie|website=The Conversation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16|last3=Ricketson|first3=Matthew|last4=Sherwood|first4=Merryn|last5=Winarnita|first5=Monika|last6=O'Donnell|first6=Penny|last7=Marjoribanks|first7=Timothy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au|title=Study follows new beats in journalism|last=Sinclair|first=Lara|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>. A second round of ARC funding allowed the research to expand internationally and New Beats II included collaborators such as [[:nl:Mark_Deuze|Professor Mark Deuze]] in the Netherlands, as well as academics in America, Canada, Indonesia and South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newbeatsblog.com/|title=New Beats|website=New Beats|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n=== Books ===\nO'Donnell, Penny (1991) ''Death Dreams & Dancing in Nicaragua,'' ABC Enterprises, Crows Nest, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, Penelope (1995) ''Dar la palabra al pueblo: La ense\u00f1anza-aprendizaje de la comunicaci\u00f3n en Nicaragua durante la Revoluci\u00f3n Popular Sandinista'' (Giving the word to the people: the teaching-learning of communication in Nicaragua during the Sandinista Popular Revolution), Universidad Iberoamericana, Mexico.\n\nO'Donnell, Penny & Simons, Lynette (1995) ''Australians against racism: Testimonies from the anti-apartheid movement in Australia,'' Pluto Press, Australia.\n\nO'Donnell, P., McKnight, D., Este, J. (2012). ''Journalism at the Speed of Bytes: Australian Newspapers in the 21st Century'', (pp. 4\u201343). Sydney, Australia: Walkley Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/meaa/docs/2012_journalism_speed_of_bytes|title=Journalism at the speed of bytes|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Submissions ===\nO'Donnell has co-authored submissions to Australian government inquiries into the media and journalism, including [[Raymond Finkelstein|Hon R Finklestein']]<nowiki/>s 2012 inquiry into media regulation, the 2017 Future of Public Interest Journalism Inquiry, and in 2018 the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers.\n\n*O'Donnell, P., Zion, L., Ricketson, M., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2018), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Work and Workers from the New Beats Project, Submission 140''.\n* Zion, L., Dodd, A., Marjoribanks, T., O'Donnell, P., Ricketson, M., Sherwood, M., Winarnita, M., Harper, R. (2017), ''New Beats Project Submission to the Senate Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 37''.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/Parliamentary_Business/Committees/Senate/Future_of_Public_Interest_Journalism/PublicInterestJournalism/Submissions|title=Submissions|last=|first=|date=|website=www.aph.gov.au|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n* Dwyer, T., Martin, F., O'Donnell, P. (2017), ''Submission to the Select Committee on the Future of Public Interest Journalism, Submission 44. June 2017''.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Selected scholarly publications ==\n\n* O'Donnell, P., Zion, L. (2019). Precarity in Media Work. In Mark Deuze, Mirjam Prenger (Eds.), ''Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions'', (pp. 223\u2013234). Amsterdam: Amsterdam University Press<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|title=Making Media: Production, Practices, and Professions|date=2019-01-14|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|year=|isbn=978-90-485-4015-0|editor-last=Deuze|editor-first=Mark|location=|pages=|doi=10.2307/j.ctvcj305r|editor-last2=Prenger|editor-first2=Mirjam}}</ref>\n* Cohen, N., Hunter, A., O'Donnell, P. (2019). Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism. ''Journalism Practice'', 13(7), (pp. 817\u2013833)<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Nicole S.|last2=Hunter|first2=Andrea|last3=O\u2019Donnell|first3=Penny|date=2019-08-09|title=Bearing the Burden of Corporate Restructuring: Job Loss and Precarious Employment in Canadian Journalism|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|journal=Journalism Practice|volume=13|issue=7|pages=817\u2013833|doi=10.1080/17512786.2019.1571937|issn=1751-2786}}</ref>\n* O'Donnell, P. (2018). Australian Journalis